To date, a singular, ‘perfect’ marriage has not been conceptualised: it is not a prime goal for high-ecclesiastical leaders and those who have lost their husbands. Women’s relations to marriage are not only juxtaposed with a Western vision of the plenitude of individual rights and mutual spousal rights, and private abundance that is the bedrock of separation, but also with clerical principles.

Thus there are many more women who are unable to divorce their men than lawyers who are able to legally grant a divorce. I realised that the major obstacle for effected women from divorcing when I arrived in Santo. There were approximately 40 women, mostly Fa’a Samoans, who came by boat, cars and vans. They told me of the horrors of state-sanctioned violence, sexual coercion, emotional abuse of children and other forms of abuse they suffered at the hands of local Vanuatu men.

To grant a divorce in Vanuatu, you might as well bet on winning a lottery. You are in denial when you suggest legal separation because women are at a financial loss. Some women have multiple children and are unable to pay financially unviable school costs. They have spent thousands of kina obtaining legal advice. They opt for lunch instead of textbooks for their children when food is available or to buy clothes for their children when they do not have money.
